Project: Investigate a Dataset - No Show Appointment¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Questions to be answered
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. We want to know what affects the patient not showing up on his appointment.

In [383]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

sns.set_style('darkgrid')
sns.set_palette("muted")

Questions to be answered¶

  • What percentages of males and females have shown up for their appointment?
  • What percentages of males and females have not shown up for their appointment?
  • What is the trend in times for patients who show up and not show up?
  • Does scholarship affect the patient decision to attend the appointment?
  • Does a certain age not show up more than other ages?
  • Does sending an SMS increase the probability of showing up?
  • Does where a person live affect their showing up?

Impressions after inspecting the dataset:¶

  • There's no null values and no duplicates in the dataset.
  • Columns like (Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap) are not useful for us and will be dropped.
  • Column PatientId type will be changed from float to int.
  • Columns like ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay need their type to be changed to datetime.
  • Columns' names are in good format and doesn't need to be renamed.

Data Cleaning¶

Drop unused column (Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap)

In [391]:
labels_drop = ["Hipertension", "Diabetes", "Alcoholism", "Handcap"]
df.drop(labels_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)

Change PatientID column type to int

In [392]:
df["PatientId"] = df["PatientId"].astype(int)

Change ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay columns type to datetime

In [393]:
df['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df["ScheduledDay"])
df['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df["AppointmentDay"])

Sending a message doesn't increase the probability of attending the appointment at all, from the 2 pie charts we notice that the patients who received an SMS didn't attend the appointment more than the patients who didn't receive an SMS.

Research Question 7 : Does where a person live affect their showing up?¶

plot number of patients and their neighbourhood who doesn't show up in their appointment

In [416]:
df_no_show["Neighbourhood"].value_counts().plot(kind="barh", figsize=(15,15))
plt.ylabel('Neighbourhoods',fontsize=16);
plt.xlabel('# of Persons', fontsize=16);
plt.title('Neighbourhood no-shows',fontsize=18);

By inspecting the above chart we see that the "JARDIM CAMBURI" neighbourhood have the highest number of patients not showing up on their appointment.

We will calculate now the percentage of patients that doesn't show up from these neighbour hoods.

In [417]:
neighbourhood_percentage = (df_no_show["Neighbourhood"].value_counts())/(df["Neighbourhood"].value_counts()) * 100
In [418]:
neighbourhood_percentage.plot(kind="barh", figsize=(15,15))
plt.ylabel('Neighbourhoods',fontsize=16);
plt.xlabel('% of Persons', fontsize=16);
plt.title('Neighbourhood no-shows',fontsize=18);

From the above chart, we see that patients from a neighbourhood like "ILHAS OCEANICAS DE TRINDADE" have a percentage of 100% of not attending their appointment.

Conclusions¶

  • Questions 1 and 2, show that gender doesn't play a role in patient attending/not attending his appointment.
  • Question 3 shows that patients with scholarships are more likely to not show up on their appointment.
  • Question 4 shows that patients are more likely to attend/not attend their appointment on 7AM (peak time) and it gradually decreases.
  • Question 5 shows that younger patients are more likely to not show up on their appointment, old patients are more likely to show up on their appointment.
  • Question 6 shows that sending an SMS message to patients doesn't increase the percentage of showing up on the appointment, but even more in this dataset, the patients who have received as SMS message didn't show up more than the patients who didn't receive an SMS.
  • Question 7 shows that the neighbourhood area affects the showing/not showing up of the patient on the appointment.
